# The Train Simulator Controller

One of my favourite type of games to play is a simulator. Especially train simulators. I'm a big fan of both the [Trainz](https://www.trainzportal.com/) and [Train Simulator](https://live.dovetailgames.com/live/train-simulator) franchises.

One thing that has always bugged me about playing these games though: Using the keyboard to control the train. With flight simulators, I can use my joy stick. With driving simulators, I can use a steering wheel. For trains, I have only come across one dedicated controller, and it's not generally available where I am.

During a trip to the [London Transport Museum](https://www.ltmuseum.co.uk/)'s [Acton Depot](https://www.ltmuseum.co.uk/visit/museum-depot) one year, I wandered out to the shack at the back, where they were selling all sorts of odds and ends. I came across a Dead Man's handle (the drivers handle). At the time I didn't really have a plan for what to do with it, but it started a small collection. Over time, I also acquired a dashboard (I think from a BR class 101), a brake handle, and a reverser key. Now, I had all the components I need to make a controller of my own.

![handles](data:image/png;base64,)

## Hardware
The hardware for this is pretty simple. It's based around an [Arduino Nano](https://store.arduino.cc/arduino-nano), which is programmed to identify itself as a keyboard. Sitting on top of that, there are:
- variable resistors for the driving and brake handle
- a 4 position switch for the reverser
- various buttons that can be either latched on or push to hold
- a 20x4 character display for output

All of this is mounted to a custom printed circuit board, with wooden mounts to hold the various controllers.

![Circuits](data:image/png;base64,)

## Software

Each input device emulates a keyboard press in software. The variable resistors have a certain voltage range that is considered to be one keystroke, and when that range changes through the threshold, a new keystroke is sent. Nothing fancy, but it works. It's all in [GitHub](https://github.com/dlpb/gamecontroller) if you want to take a look.

## Conclusion
An interesting idea, but the thing that stopped me progressing with this was the practicality of using the real life components. They're solid metal, and quite heavy, and I don't have a good way of supporting them that doesn't put unnecessary strain on the electronic components. That was the ultimate failure of this project. As a prototype it works, and I can play my train simulators with it. But the physical engineering needs improving. Maybe I will come back to that one day...
